In LaTeX, you can generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically using the `\tableofcontents` command and the `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, etc. commands from the document class. Here's a complete example:

```latex
\documentclass{report} % or book, or article (report is suitable for most cases)
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % generates the TOC

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Welcome to my document.

\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}
This section describes the methods used.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
\label{subsec:data}
Data analysis techniques employed.

\subsubsection{Data Visualization}
\label{subsubsec:visual}
Visualizing the data.

\section{Results}
\includegraphics{figure1.pdf} % optional (for keeping it brief)
\label{sec:results}

\backmatter
\appendix
\section{Additional Information}
Appendix text.

\end{document}
```

In this example:

1. We use the `report` document class (you can switch to `article` if your document is short).
2. The `\tableofcontents` command is included where you want the TOC to appear in your document.
3. Sectioning commands like `\section`, `\subsection`, and `\subsubsection` are used to define the document structure.
4. (Optional) Labels are added to each sectioning command (e.g., `\label{sec:intro}`) to allow cross-referencing, but they're not essential for the TOC generation.

When you run LaTeX (e.g., `pdflatex mydocument.tex`) on this code, it will compile the document and generate a table of contents that includes all the section headings. The TOC will be updated automatically.

Note: Make sure to run LaTeX twice to get the TOC updated correctly (the first run generates the table of contents, and the second run updates the page numbers).

